{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a7ebc3c6-ed26-44b1-aa08-6770a7902748","content":"Use `dotnet watch` to re-run tests automatically on every file save:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nDrop the `--filter` to run all tests on each change. Every time you save `InventoryServiceTests.cs`, the tests rebuild and re-execute.\n\n**Quick note on your failing test:** `RemoveStock` silently subtracts without checking availability. It needs a guard to throw when `quantity` exceeds current stock. For example:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply that fix?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bef7e248-9b11-40aa-9d02-6b877fe095b3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for rapid iteration. Since this is a .NET test project using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (configured in global.json), I can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to enable hot reload.\n\nWith .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test` supports `--hotreload` flag. But the more traditional approach is `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me suggest `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests on file save. That's the standard hot reload approach for test projects.\n\nActually, with .NET 10 and the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner, there's a newer `dotnet test --hotreload` option.","outputTokens":442},"id":"16d9fabd-2793-4668-8ab6-39b6d4c3bb23","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:20:59.851Z","parentId":"6abcf09d-786c-4225-bd67-b91888c11fd1"}
